1
00:00:00,650 --> 00:00:01,650
Hello and welcome.

2
00:00:01,650 --> 00:00:07,470
Today I’m sharing how to find high probability
bullish and bearish pressure areas using simple

3
00:00:07,470 --> 00:00:13,320
price action, and I will reveal how to day
trade these zones, in multiple market scenarios.

4
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:19,460
So if you could, like, subscribe to the channel,
and stick around for the full video.

5
00:00:19,460 --> 00:00:24,300
Candlesticks shadows can tell you a lot about
the psychology of market participants and

6
00:00:24,300 --> 00:00:27,490
should play an important role in your analysis.

7
00:00:27,490 --> 00:00:30,619
Long upper shadows are considered bearish
shadows.

8
00:00:30,619 --> 00:00:36,150
The presence of one or more bearish shadows
after a price advance demonstrates that the

9
00:00:36,150 --> 00:00:38,730
market could possible reaching a top.

10
00:00:38,730 --> 00:00:43,800
There is not enough demand at higher prices
to continue to move the price upward, at least

11
00:00:43,800 --> 00:00:45,650
for the short term.

12
00:00:45,650 --> 00:00:49,280
Long lower shadows are considered bullish
shadows.

13
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:55,260
The formation of one or more bullish shadows
after a price decline, especially near support,

14
00:00:55,260 --> 00:00:58,670
shows us visually that the market could be
reaching a bottom.

15
00:00:58,670 --> 00:01:03,280
In this case, the wick indicates that lower
prices are being rejected.

16
00:01:03,280 --> 00:01:05,290
The Psychology Behind A Wick

17
00:01:05,290 --> 00:01:06,990
I’ve said it a previous video.

18
00:01:06,990 --> 00:01:09,960
Markets are traders making trading decisions.

19
00:01:09,960 --> 00:01:14,330
If you really want to succeed at day trading,
when you look at a chart, don’t see it as

20
00:01:14,330 --> 00:01:15,850
price movement.

21
00:01:15,850 --> 00:01:18,170
See it as traders making decisions.

22
00:01:18,170 --> 00:01:24,420
So let’s analyze three stages of a Pin Bar,
from the perspective of other traders.

23
00:01:24,420 --> 00:01:29,120
How do traders react to this bar, during and
after its formation?

24
00:01:29,120 --> 00:01:33,950
The best way to examine this price bar is
to consider the perspective of traders who

25
00:01:33,950 --> 00:01:37,000
transacted at the extremes of the bar.

26
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,670
• Group 1 – Sold at the bar high
• Group 2 – Bought at the bar high

27
00:01:41,670 --> 00:01:49,150
• Group 3 – Sold at the bar low
• Group 4 – Bought at the bar low

28
00:01:49,150 --> 00:01:54,610
Traders who sold at the high of the bar (Stage
One) felt like geniuses in Stage Two.

29
00:01:54,610 --> 00:02:01,229
Then, they quickly became frustrated as the
market moved higher and erased their profits.

30
00:02:01,229 --> 00:02:06,080
Traders who bought at the high of the bar
(Stage One) were constantly watching the bar

31
00:02:06,080 --> 00:02:08,400
erode their trading account.

32
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:10,619
Stage Two was the worst time for them.

33
00:02:10,619 --> 00:02:15,550
In stage 3 they felt extremely relieved when
the bar ended the way it did.

34
00:02:15,550 --> 00:02:20,620
Traders who sold at the low of the bar (Stage
Two) are in the worst case scenario.

35
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:24,099
The market did not move a single tick in their
favor.

36
00:02:24,099 --> 00:02:28,409
Traders who bought at the low of the Bar (Stage
Two) are the happiest.

37
00:02:28,409 --> 00:02:31,049
They did not suffer a single tick against
them.

38
00:02:31,049 --> 00:02:36,319
So, in the case of a large wick candle, we
have 4 types of traders.

39
00:02:36,319 --> 00:02:37,319
1.

40
00:02:37,319 --> 00:02:40,659
Sellers who are scared (likely to cover shorts)
2.

41
00:02:40,659 --> 00:02:43,769
Buyers who are optimistic (likely to hold
longs)

42
00:02:43,769 --> 00:02:44,769
3.

43
00:02:44,769 --> 00:02:47,779
Sellers who are demoralized (likely to cover
shorts)

44
00:02:47,779 --> 00:02:48,779
4.

45
00:02:48,779 --> 00:02:52,790
Buyers who are confident (likely to hold longs
or even add more)

46
00:02:52,790 --> 00:02:54,150
Why is this important?

47
00:02:54,150 --> 00:02:58,219
Well, together, they are likely to produce
buying pressure.

48
00:02:58,219 --> 00:03:02,709
The traders who are short want to cover, so
they are creating demand.

49
00:03:02,709 --> 00:03:08,950
The buyers want to hold, so they are not supplying,
at least not without demanding higher prices.

50
00:03:08,950 --> 00:03:11,780
The result is a pressure on the market to
move up.

51
00:03:11,780 --> 00:03:15,969
So, the lower shadow reflects the amount of
buying pressure.

52
00:03:15,969 --> 00:03:22,249
You job is to locate the buying and selling
pressure zones implied by the lower and upper

53
00:03:22,249 --> 00:03:24,370
shadows of price bars.

54
00:03:24,370 --> 00:03:29,900
Although in the previous case, I used a Pin
Bar as an example, a strong Pressure Zone

55
00:03:29,900 --> 00:03:32,909
is not defined just by one Pin Bar.

56
00:03:32,909 --> 00:03:38,090
To find high probability Pressure Zones, you
must not be particularly interested in how

57
00:03:38,090 --> 00:03:39,829
a single bar looks.

58
00:03:39,829 --> 00:03:44,200
You must pay more attention to the appearance
of a group of price bars.

59
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:45,719
7.2 - Identifying the Pressure Zone

60
00:03:45,719 --> 00:03:50,739
So the buying or selling pressure found on
a single price bar might not be sufficiently

61
00:03:50,739 --> 00:03:52,969
reliable for a trading setup.

62
00:03:52,969 --> 00:03:58,919
Therefore, instead of a single bar, look for
at least three consecutive bars with overlapping

63
00:03:58,919 --> 00:04:01,139
upper or lower shadows.

64
00:04:01,139 --> 00:04:05,290
Remember, shadows indicate potential buying
or selling pressure.

65
00:04:05,290 --> 00:04:10,609
When shadows overlap, they create a price
zone that is more likely to exhibit the buying

66
00:04:10,609 --> 00:04:13,430
or selling pressure you anticipate.

67
00:04:13,430 --> 00:04:17,130
Consider the perspectives of the four groups
of traders again.

68
00:04:17,130 --> 00:04:23,039
When we have three consecutive bars with overlapping
lower shadows, the traders undergo the same

69
00:04:23,039 --> 00:04:28,199
emotional cycle three times, all within a
compact price range.

70
00:04:28,199 --> 00:04:36,789
That price range is the Pressure Zone we are
looking for.

71
00:04:36,789 --> 00:04:40,100
A bullish Pressure Zone is easy to identify.

72
00:04:40,100 --> 00:04:43,830
You can mark it out as a zone on your charts
1.

73
00:04:43,830 --> 00:04:47,659
Find three consecutive bars with overlapping
lower shadows.

74
00:04:47,659 --> 00:04:48,659
2.

75
00:04:48,659 --> 00:04:51,280
Mark out the lowest low among the three bars.

76
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:52,280
3.

77
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:56,389
Mark out the lowest closing price of the three
candle bodies (exclude the shadows).

78
00:04:56,389 --> 00:04:57,389
4.

79
00:04:57,389 --> 00:05:08,229
The area between these two price levels is
the bullish Pressure Zone.

80
00:05:08,229 --> 00:05:10,729
To find a bearish Pressure Zone
1.

81
00:05:10,729 --> 00:05:14,330
Find three consecutive bars with overlapping
upper shadows.

82
00:05:14,330 --> 00:05:15,330
2.

83
00:05:15,330 --> 00:05:18,520
Mark out the highest high among the three
bars.

84
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:19,520
3.

85
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:24,120
Mark out the highest close of the three candle
bodies (exclude the shadows).

86
00:05:24,120 --> 00:05:25,120
4.

87
00:05:25,120 --> 00:05:29,599
The area between these two price levels is
the bearish Pressure Zone.

88
00:05:29,599 --> 00:05:30,599
Very important.

89
00:05:30,599 --> 00:05:35,360
Small overlaps of shadows can create unreliable
Pressure Zones.

90
00:05:35,360 --> 00:05:40,580
To avoid them, ignore overlaps below a certain
threshold.

91
00:05:40,580 --> 00:05:46,000
For trading higher time frames (1 hour and
above), consider increasing the threshold

92
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:47,110
as necessary.

93
00:05:47,110 --> 00:05:51,370
Here’s the Long Pressure Zone Trading Plan
1.

94
00:05:51,370 --> 00:05:53,470
Find a Bullish Pressure Zone
2.

95
00:05:53,470 --> 00:05:58,949
Buy above the next bullish bar that overlaps
with the Pressure Zone and closes above it

96
00:05:58,949 --> 00:06:04,389
(The third bar of the Pressure Zone is acceptable
if it is bullish.)

97
00:06:04,389 --> 00:06:10,080
If the price returns once again to the bullish
pressure zone and forms another signal candle,

98
00:06:10,080 --> 00:06:11,560
you can re-enter.

99
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:14,050
This is similar to supply and demand trading.

100
00:06:14,050 --> 00:06:15,050
3.

101
00:06:15,050 --> 00:06:20,310
If price breaks below the Pressure Zone, the
setup becomes invalid.

102
00:06:20,310 --> 00:06:22,840
And here’s the Short Pressure Zone Trading
Plan

103
00:06:22,840 --> 00:06:24,320
1.

104
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:26,680
Find a Bearish Pressure Zone
2.

105
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:32,310
Sell below the next bearish bar that overlaps
with the Pressure Zone and closes below it.

106
00:06:32,310 --> 00:06:37,490
(The third bar of the Pressure Zone is acceptable
if it is bearish.)

107
00:06:37,490 --> 00:06:43,020
If the price returns once again to the bearish
pressure zone and forms another signal candle,

108
00:06:43,020 --> 00:06:44,759
you can re-enter.
3.

109
00:06:44,759 --> 00:06:49,940
If price breaks above the Pressure Zone, the
setup becomes invalid.

110
00:06:49,940 --> 00:06:51,620
Here we have an uptrend.

111
00:06:51,620 --> 00:06:56,759
This swing high maintained the excellent bullish
momentum by moving above the previous swing

112
00:06:56,759 --> 00:06:58,080
high.

113
00:06:58,080 --> 00:07:04,030
After such a bullish move, expect the market
to react with some bearish or sideways action.

114
00:07:04,030 --> 00:07:09,120
This low that formed could not close below
the previous pivot low, implying that uptrend

115
00:07:09,120 --> 00:07:10,120
is still intact.

116
00:07:10,120 --> 00:07:12,990
And here’s our bullish Pressure Zone.

117
00:07:12,990 --> 00:07:18,469
These consecutive wicks signify that sellers
were able to push the price down.

118
00:07:18,469 --> 00:07:21,960
Bulls drove price back up, showing strength.

119
00:07:21,960 --> 00:07:26,900
Since bulls overpowered the selling pressure
by bears, there is the potential that their

120
00:07:26,900 --> 00:07:32,410
strength will carry forward leading to an
upwards movement in price.

121
00:07:32,410 --> 00:07:37,599
This is the signal candle, which overlaps
with our pressure zone, so we buy above it.

122
00:07:37,599 --> 00:07:43,729
The low of this extended wick provides a very
prudent level for you to place your stop.

123
00:07:43,729 --> 00:07:48,669
The rationale for that stop placement being
that sellers pushed price to the low of that

124
00:07:48,669 --> 00:07:51,750
wick but could not push it beyond that point.

125
00:07:51,750 --> 00:07:56,680
Hence, placing the stop just below that wick
is a level that has a lower likelihood of

126
00:07:56,680 --> 00:07:58,389
getting hit.

127
00:07:58,389 --> 00:08:00,029
How Do You Know When to Exit?

128
00:08:00,029 --> 00:08:04,810
This is probably the most difficult question
to answer; it will depend based upon your

129
00:08:04,810 --> 00:08:06,490
risk tolerance.

130
00:08:06,490 --> 00:08:10,330
Sometimes it’s best to take your profit
quickly and walk away.

131
00:08:10,330 --> 00:08:14,939
Other times you want to take some money off
the table, move the stop to breakeven and

132
00:08:14,939 --> 00:08:16,650
let the trade run.

133
00:08:16,650 --> 00:08:19,889
This discretion will be up to you.

134
00:08:19,889 --> 00:08:23,439
This example shows a bearish Pressure Zone
setup.

135
00:08:23,439 --> 00:08:29,160
These three bars formed the Pressure Zone
and gave us an opportunity to short the market.

136
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:34,700
This was the setup bar, as it overlapped the
area and was also bearish.

137
00:08:34,700 --> 00:08:37,370
The short trade had decent follow-through.

138
00:08:37,370 --> 00:08:42,480
And as the market pulled back upwards once
again, this was an excellent option, especially

139
00:08:42,480 --> 00:08:47,590
for traders who missed the first bearish Pressure
Zone setup.

140
00:08:47,590 --> 00:08:52,590
The advantage of this strategy is that the
Pressure Zone places less emphasis on the

141
00:08:52,590 --> 00:08:59,380
length of a single shadow and instead focuses
on multiple shadows to find reliable signs

142
00:08:59,380 --> 00:09:01,830
of bullish or bearish pressure.

143
00:09:01,830 --> 00:09:05,910
But, this price pattern has an important drawback.

144
00:09:05,910 --> 00:09:12,470
Consecutive bars with overlapping shadows
also occur frequently within congested markets.

145
00:09:12,470 --> 00:09:17,440
Instead of taking signals and trades all over
the place, the better trades usually happen

146
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:22,120
at key price levels and when you also take
volume into account.

147
00:09:22,120 --> 00:09:28,330
So location of the pressure zones and volume
are very important to filter those bad zones,

148
00:09:28,330 --> 00:09:30,470
that are offering false signals.

149
00:09:30,470 --> 00:09:33,930
A good filter would be a common moving average.

150
00:09:33,930 --> 00:09:41,090
200, 100, 50 period moving averages or even
VWAP are worth having on your charts when

151
00:09:41,090 --> 00:09:43,640
it comes to finding key pressure zones.

152
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:49,670
During ranges, moving averages lose some of
their validity, but during trending markets,

153
00:09:49,670 --> 00:09:53,660
you’ll see that those moving averages will
work very accurately.

154
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:59,890
So try to buy bullish pressure zones, above
a common moving average and sell a bearish

155
00:09:59,890 --> 00:10:34,400
pressure zone below a common moving average.

156
00:10:34,400 --> 00:10:38,730
Higher timeframe support and resistance levels
and zones add a great layer of additional

157
00:10:38,730 --> 00:10:42,190
confirmation and confluence to these pressure
zones.

158
00:10:42,190 --> 00:10:47,750
I especially look for strong and impulsive
turning points where price has previously

159
00:10:47,750 --> 00:10:53,570
shown a strong reaction because it implies
that there is a lot of buyer and seller interest

160
00:10:53,570 --> 00:11:29,930
in such an area and price is likely to show
another reaction as well.

161
00:11:29,930 --> 00:11:33,950
Trendlines and channels are also great confluence
areas.

162
00:11:33,950 --> 00:11:38,760
Trendlines are especially valuable if you
are looking for potential pressure zones during

163
00:11:38,760 --> 00:11:44,700
trending markets, when it comes to finding
re-entry opportunities during pullbacks.

164
00:11:44,700 --> 00:12:21,950
When it comes to drawing trendlines, go for
the most obvious ones with the most touches.

165
00:12:21,950 --> 00:12:26,940
My favorite dynamic support and resistance
levels are pivot points.

166
00:12:26,940 --> 00:12:31,450
Pivot points are based on previous day’s
high, low and close so they don’t change

167
00:12:31,450 --> 00:12:32,830
throughout the current day.

168
00:12:32,830 --> 00:12:38,190
I mostly pay attention to the central pivot
point and S1 and R1 levels.

169
00:12:38,190 --> 00:12:43,630
So when you spot a pressure zone that forms
at a pivot level, that’s a high probability

170
00:12:43,630 --> 00:12:44,630
trade.

171
00:12:44,630 --> 00:12:48,250
Also, the take profit aspect becomes much
easier.

172
00:12:48,250 --> 00:13:23,790
You exit a part of your position at the next
pivot levels.

173
00:13:23,790 --> 00:13:27,140
If you found value and learned something new,
leave us a like.

174
00:13:27,140 --> 00:13:30,760
This way we’ll know if you'd like to see
more videos like this one.

175
00:13:30,760 --> 00:13:34,970
And check out our academy program if you want
to further level up your trading.

176
00:13:34,970 --> 00:13:36,050
Until next time.

